english:
  title: Seeing Off Jeong Jeong-eon Geuk-in as He Resigns from Office and Returns to His Homeland
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    You came in a whirlwind, now you depart with boundless ease—
    Do not weigh your comings and goings by right and wrong.
    Though in your twilight years you've grown full on the dust of the world,
    Spring rain upon the ferns of your native mountains holds more worth.

    No official rank could ever truly bind you—
    Why should monkey and crane begrudge their complaints to paper?
    Your horse's hooves press slowly through the snow as you go,
    And when you turn to look back, the palace walls fade into distant clouds.
  footnotes:
    - The 'monkey and crane' alludes to a famous poem of protest and regret, here suggesting that even nature itself would envy his freedom
    - The reference to 'dust of the world' (塵世) is a Buddhist metaphor for the illusions and attachments of secular life
